    bestFor:"First-time Ethiopia visitors, history lovers, cultural travelers",
    overview:"The Classic Northern Ethiopia circuit takes you through four thousand years of African civilisation — from the island monasteries of Lake Tana through the royal castles of Gondar to the rock-hewn churches of Lalibela. This is the journey that defines Ethiopia for most international travelers, and with good reason: nowhere else in Africa can you experience this depth of living historical culture in such a concentrated geography. Every site is still in active use — the churches are still prayed in, the monasteries still inhabited, the ceremonies still observed.",
    highlights:["Lalibela's eleven rock-hewn churches, still in active daily worship","Island monasteries of Lake Tana, reached by boat","Fasil Ghebbi royal enclosure in Gondar","Debre Berhan Selassie — the painted ceiling of angels","Blue Nile Falls at Tis Abay","Private guide and vehicle throughout"],
    journeyNarrative:"Classic Northern Ethiopia is the itinerary we build most often, and for good reason: it is the most complete introduction to why Ethiopia matters historically, without asking a first-time visitor to take on the physical demands of the true frontier regions. It suits travelers who want depth — real time in each place, not a photo stop — but who also want the reassurance of domestic flights over long overland drives and comfortable, well-established hotels every night. If you leave Ethiopia understanding only one thing, it should be this: nothing here was built for tourism. The castles were built by kings who ruled from them, the churches are still prayed in by the people who carved them, and that continuity — not the age of the stone alone — is what makes the north worth the ten days.",
