    days:[
      {day:1,title:"Arrive Addis Ababa",location:"Addis Ababa",description:"Arrival, transfer, and a briefing on Omo Valley communities and protocols.",orientation:"The trip opens with orientation rather than activity — a clear, honest briefing on who you'll meet and how to meet them respectfully.",experience:"Your Sawla guide meets you on arrival and uses the evening to walk through the Hamar and Karo communities specifically: how greetings work, when and how photography is appropriate, and how payment for photographs is handled through your guide rather than negotiated directly. With only six days ahead, this briefing does real work — there's little slack later to explain things you could have asked about now.",paceNotes:"An easy first day — international arrival, transfer, and an evening briefing, nothing physically demanding.",fieldNote:"Because this itinerary moves quickly, ask every question you have tonight. Your guide would rather spend twenty extra minutes here than have you unsure of etiquette on day three.",accommodation:"Comfortable city hotel in Addis Ababa",travelTime:"International arrival — no internal travel today",walkingLevel:"None",overnight:"Addis Ababa"},
      {day:2,title:"Fly to Jinka — Orientation",location:"Jinka",description:"Morning flight south. Afternoon gentle first encounter and orientation near Jinka.",orientation:"The flight south is a genuine transition — from highland Addis to the hotter, slower rhythm of the southern Omo Valley.",experience:"A morning flight brings you to Jinka, the practical gateway to the southern communities and the last town with reliable services before the roads and the pace both change. The afternoon is used deliberately gently: a short, easy first encounter near town to let you settle into the heat and the different social rhythms of the south before the more involved days ahead.",paceNotes:"A lighter day by design — flight and short transfer, with an easy afternoon rather than a full activity slate.",fieldNote:"Your local Jinka-based guide, distinct from your main Sawla guide, is the one whose personal relationships with Hamar and Karo families actually make the following days work.",accommodation:"Basic but comfortable guesthouse in Jinka",travelTime:"~1 hour flight Addis Ababa–Jinka",walkingLevel:"Light",overnight:"Jinka"},
      {day:3,title:"Karo on the Omo River",location:"Omo River",description:"Drive to the Karo people — elaborate body painting and the Omo River setting.",orientation:"A drive to the Omo River banks and the Karo, the smallest of the valley's major communities and among its most visually inventive in body painting.",experience:"The Karo live directly on the river and paint their bodies and faces daily with white chalk, charcoal, and ochre in patterns that are genuinely improvised rather than fixed — no two days look quite the same. Villages sit on low bluffs above the water, and your guide's personal relationship with a specific community here allows a slower, more conversational visit than most day-trippers get, with real time to sit and talk before any camera comes out.",paceNotes:"A driving day more than a walking one — several hours on unpaved road, with a relaxed visit once you arrive.",fieldNote:"Karo etiquette is generally more relaxed than some neighboring communities', but individual consent for photographs still matters, especially with children — always ask, and let your guide handle any payment discussion.",accommodation:"Simple guesthouse in Turmi",travelTime:"Several hours on unpaved road from Jinka to the Omo River area, continuing to Turmi",walkingLevel:"Light",overnight:"Turmi"},
      {day:4,title:"Hamar Community",location:"Turmi",description:"Full day with the Hamar — ochre-braided hair, coil jewellery, and genuine community relationships.",orientation:"A full day with the Hamar, the Omo Valley's most numerous community, built around actual time together rather than a single photographed moment.",experience:"Hamar villages around Turmi are where your guide's longest-standing relationships in the region are based, and the day reflects that: time spent in ordinary settings, watching cattle herding and daily chores, talking through a translator about how life here has and hasn't changed, and observing the distinctive ochre-and-butter hairstyling Hamar women maintain. It's a day built on conversation as much as visual interest.",paceNotes:"A gentle day physically — mostly walking on flat ground between homesteads, with plenty of sitting and talking.",conditionalNotes:"If a bull-jumping ceremony happens to be scheduled nearby during your visit, your guide will know and can arrange respectful attendance — but this itinerary does not promise or stage one; ceremonies are set by individual families on their own timing.",fieldNote:"Coil jewelry and braided ochre hair are markers of specific life stages among Hamar women — ask, and your guide will explain what you're actually looking at rather than leaving it as decoration.",accommodation:"Same simple guesthouse in Turmi",travelTime:"Short drives between villages, generally under 30 minutes",walkingLevel:"Light to moderate",overnight:"Turmi"},
      {day:5,title:"Turmi Market",location:"Turmi",description:"The weekly Hamar market at Turmi.",orientation:"The most important weekly market in the southern Omo Valley — a genuine trading event, not a display staged for visitors.",experience:"Communities travel in from across the surrounding area to trade grain, livestock, tobacco, and jewelry at Turmi's market, and very little of what happens here has anything to do with tourism. It's one of the most unfiltered windows into ordinary Omo Valley economic life on the whole trip — negotiation, gossip, and the practical business of a rural market square operating exactly as it would with or without visitors present.",paceNotes:"An easy day on foot around the market grounds — dust, crowds, and uneven ground are the main physical factors.",conditionalNotes:"This day is scheduled to land on the market's actual weekly day — your guide adjusts the surrounding sequence as needed so the visit isn't forced onto the wrong day of the week.",fieldNote:"Market days call for a different, calmer camera etiquette than community-visit days: photograph general scenes freely, but still ask before any individual portrait.",accommodation:"Basic but comfortable guesthouse in Jinka",travelTime:"Drive back from Turmi to Jinka after the market, roughly 3–4 hours on unpaved road",walkingLevel:"Light to moderate — dusty, crowded ground",overnight:"Jinka"},
      {day:6,title:"Fly to Addis Ababa and Depart",location:"Addis Ababa",description:"Morning flight north and international connection.",orientation:"The return flight north and, depending on timing, your international departure.",experience:"A morning flight brings you back to Addis Ababa. Depending on your international flight time, there may be a few hours free before your guide transfers you to Bole International Airport for your onward connection.",paceNotes:"A light final day — a flight and a transfer, with timing dependent on your specific international departure.",accommodation:"Departure — no overnight, unless your flight timing requires an additional night in Addis",travelTime:"~1 hour flight Jinka–Addis Ababa",walkingLevel:"Light"},
    ],
    goodToKnow:["Private journey — dates, pace, and accommodation tailored to you","Domestic flights coordinated by Sawla Tours","Private licensed guide and 4WD vehicle throughout","Inclusions and a full quote provided on enquiry","No booking fee to enquire — we respond within 24 hours"],
