    overview:"A short, intense expedition to one of the few persistent lava lakes on earth. Erta Ale is an active shield volcano in the Danakil Depression, reached by driving across salt flats and night-hiking to the crater rim. Maximum spectacle, minimum days.",
    highlights:["Erta Ale active lava lake at night","The glow of molten rock in complete darkness","Afar salt-flat landscape","Full expedition logistics and armed Afar escort","Maximum spectacle, minimum days"],
    journeyNarrative:"This is the fastest way to stand at the rim of an active lava lake — four days, no detours, built for travelers who want the single most extraordinary sight in the Danakil without the longer circuit around it. It suits people who are genuinely fit and comfortable with real heat and a demanding night hike, more than it suits anyone looking for a gentle add-on excursion. There is very little slack in this itinerary: nearly every day is either travel or the ascent itself, so it rewards travelers who arrive already prepared rather than needing time to ease in.",
    routeIntelligence:[
      "Mekelle is used as the staging point rather than a direct desert entry from Addis, giving time for final equipment checks before the demanding sector ahead, even on this short a trip.",
      "The salt-flat crossing to Erta Ale's base is scheduled for daytime, with the physically hardest activity — the ascent itself — held back for after dark specifically to avoid the worst of the heat.",
      "The Erta Ale climb is timed at night because daytime temperatures in the Danakil regularly exceed 45°C, and the identical climb in full sun would be genuinely dangerous rather than merely uncomfortable.",
      "Because this is a compressed itinerary with minimal buffer days, it depends more than most on current regional access and ground conditions being confirmed suitable close to your travel dates.",
      "The return drive follows immediately after the descent rather than a rest day, which is part of why this trip is honestly rated Challenging despite its short length — there is real physical load packed into four days.",
    ],
    accommodationApproach:[
      "Mekelle: comfortable hotel before and after the Danakil sector",
      "Danakil Depression: expedition-grade desert camp — simple mattresses under open sky or light shelter, minimal facilities, genuine expedition camping",
    ],
    days:[
      {day:1,title:"Arrive Addis Ababa — Fly to Mekelle",location:"Mekelle",description:"Arrival and onward flight north. Briefing and gear check in Mekelle.",orientation:"A compressed opening day: international arrival and an immediate onward flight, since this short itinerary has no spare time to lose.",experience:"On arrival in Addis Ababa you connect directly to a domestic flight north to Mekelle, the staging point for the Danakil sector. That evening, your guide runs through the expedition in full honesty — the heat, the physical demands of the night ascent ahead, current ground conditions, and the equipment you'll need — while your gear is checked over before heading into the desert.",paceNotes:"A travel-heavy day with essentially no walking; save your energy, since the demanding days start almost immediately.",fieldNote:"Mention any heart, respiratory, or heat-sensitivity concerns tonight — there's no buffer day later in this itinerary to reconsider.",accommodation:"Comfortable hotel in Mekelle",travelTime:"International arrival, then ~1.5 hour flight Addis Ababa–Mekelle",walkingLevel:"None",overnight:"Mekelle"},
      {day:2,title:"Drive to Erta Ale Base",location:"Danakil Depression",description:"Cross the extraordinary Danakil salt flats by 4WD convoy.",orientation:"The day that actually enters the Danakil Depression — a landscape that only becomes real once you're inside it.",experience:"The 4WD convoy crosses the salt flats toward Erta Ale's base, passing camel caravans still hauling hand-cut salt slabs out of the depression exactly as generations of traders have before them. Heat builds steadily through the day in one of the hottest inhabited landscapes on Earth, and the pace is deliberately slow and shaded wherever possible — today exists to conserve energy for tonight's ascent, not to pack in sightseeing.",paceNotes:"A long, hot drive on rough tracks for the final stretch. Rest seriously in the afternoon heat; conserving energy today matters more than it looks.",conditionalNotes:"Daytime temperatures in the Danakil regularly exceed 45°C, among the hottest inhabited conditions on Earth. Heat exhaustion and dehydration are genuine risks — drink far more water than feels necessary and tell your guide immediately if you feel unusually fatigued, nauseous, or stop sweating.",fieldNote:"Sleep or rest through the hottest part of the afternoon even if it feels unproductive — tonight's ascent is the most physically demanding single activity most travelers will do on this trip.",accommodation:"Expedition-grade desert camp at the base of Erta Ale — simple mattresses under open sky, minimal facilities",travelTime:"~5–6 hours total driving, rough tracks for the final sector",walkingLevel:"Light today; the demanding walking is tonight",overnight:"Danakil (desert camp)"},
      {day:3,title:"Lava Lake and Return Drive",location:"Erta Ale",description:"Night-hike to the crater rim for the lava lake. Descend before sunrise and begin the return drive.",orientation:"The night this entire trip is built around: an actual lake of molten lava, reached by a demanding climb undertaken specifically after dark.",experience:"You set out well after nightfall, climbing roughly three hours up Erta Ale's slope by headlamp — a deliberate choice, since the same ascent in daytime heat would be genuinely dangerous rather than merely uncomfortable. Then the crater rim opens and there it is: an active lava lake, glowing and visibly moving, its heat reaching your face from a safe but real distance. After resting a few hours near the summit, you descend at first light and begin the long drive back toward Mekelle the same day, trading the volcano's heat for the comparative comfort of a real bed by evening.",paceNotes:"The portfolio's most demanding day — multi-hour night climb on loose volcanic rock, early descent on tired legs, and a full day's drive. Fitness and sure-footedness required.",conditionalNotes:"Erta Ale's activity level varies — the lava lake is generally reliable but volcanic conditions can shift with little notice, and access is confirmed by your guide's ground team before the ascent begins each night, not guaranteed in advance.",fieldNote:"Bring a headlamp with fresh batteries and a spare — this is not optional equipment, and losing light partway up is a genuine problem, not an inconvenience.",accommodation:"Comfortable hotel in Mekelle",travelTime:"~3 hour ascent, short rest, dawn descent, then a full day's drive back to Mekelle",walkingLevel:"Full, demanding night hike over loose volcanic rock; not suitable for travelers with mobility limitations or significant fitness concerns",overnight:"Mekelle"},
      {day:4,title:"Fly to Addis Ababa and Depart",location:"Addis Ababa",description:"Fly to Addis and connect with your onward flight.",orientation:"A short flight closes out the expedition, returning you to Addis Ababa in time for your international connection.",experience:"A morning flight brings you back to Addis Ababa, where your guide transfers you to Bole International Airport for your onward or international flight — the lava lake now behind you after one of the most physically intense short trips Sawla offers.",paceNotes:"Timing depends on your specific international flight.",accommodation:"Departure — no overnight",travelTime:"~1.5 hour flight Mekelle–Addis Ababa",walkingLevel:"None"},
    ],
    goodToKnow:["Private journey — dates, pace, and accommodation tailored to you","Domestic flights coordinated by Sawla Tours","Private licensed guide and 4WD vehicle throughout","Inclusions and a full quote provided on enquiry","No booking fee to enquire — we respond within 24 hours"],
