    highlights:["Sanetti Plateau trekking with Ethiopian wolves","Harenna cloud-forest descent","Mountain nyala and endemic Bale birds","Fewer crowds than the Simien","Dramatic habitat transitions on foot","Colobus monkeys in the Harenna canopy"],
    journeyNarrative:"This is a trek for travelers who want the Simien's altitude and endemic wildlife without its crowds — the Bale Mountains see a fraction of the visitors, and the walking here moves through arguably the most dramatic single habitat transition in Africa, from the frozen-feeling Afroalpine moorland of the Sanetti Plateau down into ancient Harenna cloud forest in the space of two days on foot. It suits genuinely fit travelers comfortable with cold, thin air at close to 4,000m and are honest that the Ethiopian wolf — the rarest canid on Earth — is a possibility here, a good one, but never a guarantee. Anyone with serious heart or lung conditions should discuss this trip carefully with their doctor before booking; the altitude here is real, not incidental.",
